  "comparison_plan": {
    "consensus_problem": {
      "paxos": "Paxos solves the generic consensus problem: enabling a distributed group to agree on a single value despite node failures, provided a majority remains available. Basic Paxos guarantees safety (only one value is decided) but not liveness, as competing proposers can prevent progress indefinitely. Multi-Paxos extends this to replicated logs by establishing a stable leader to amortize the Prepare phase across many decisions.",
      "raft": "Raft solves the replicated state machine problem: enabling a distributed group to maintain a consistent log of commands across multiple nodes. Raft is designed to address leader election, log replication, and safety, ensuring that all nodes apply the same sequence of commands in the same order."
    },
    "leadership_behavior": {
      "paxos": "Paxos does not have a built-in stable leader role. Instead, Paxos uses proposers (any node can propose values) and acceptors (nodes that vote on proposals). Leaders can be emulated in Multi-Paxos by designating a stable proposer to reduce the overhead of the Prepare phase, but this is not a core abstraction of the protocol. Multiple proposers can coexist and compete, which can lead to liveness issues.",
      "raft": "Raft explicitly elects and uses a leader in each term. In each term, at most one leader is elected through a randomized election timeout mechanism. The leader receives client requests, appends them to its log, and replicates entries to followers. This leader-based approach ensures clear coordination and simplifies the protocol's logic."
    },
    "majority_requirement": {
      "shared_principle": "Both Paxos and Raft require a quorum of size > N/2 servers (a strict majority) to guarantee safety and progress. A majority must be available for the system to make progress.",
      "paxos_specifics": "In Paxos, the majority requirement is enforced through the two-phase protocol: Phase 1 (Prepare/Promise) requires a majority of acceptors to promise not to accept lower-numbered proposals, and Phase 2 (Accept/Accepted) requires a majority of acceptors to accept the proposed value. Safety is guaranteed because any two majorities must overlap, ensuring that a previously accepted value is discovered.",
      "raft_specifics": "In Raft, the majority requirement is used in two critical contexts: (1) Leader election—a candidate must receive votes from a majority of nodes to become leader; (2) Log entry commitment—an entry is committed only when it is replicated to a majority of nodes. Once committed, entries are guaranteed to be durable and will eventually be applied by all nodes. Raft's AppendEntries RPC is the mechanism by which the leader replicates entries and receives acknowledgments from followers, ensuring majority replication before commitment."
    }
  }
}

